1 wild life habitat and reduce water flow into the North Canadian River
2 waterways and water basins.
3 C. In administering the pilot program, the Commission shall:
4 1. Cooperate with landowners, state agencies, and other
5 political subdivisions for removal of harmful woody species;
6 2. Measure the density of harmful woody species and estimate
7 water used by those species;
8 3. Create a study using a parallel watershed with no control of
9 harmful woody species;
10 4. Utilize available funds to cost-share with landowners,
11 recognized governmental entities, or not-for-profit organizations
12 for expenses incurred in the eradication of harmful woody species by
13 prescribed burn, biological controls, mechanical removal, or
14 herbicide applications;
15 5. Develop grant programs with conservation districts, rural
16 fire departments, and prescribe burn associations for resources
17 needed for prescribed burns, mechanical removal, biological control,
18 or herbicide applications on harmful woody species;
19 6. Bring attention to the problems posed by harmful woody
20 species to create awareness, demonstrate value to all stakeholders,
21 and encourage landowners to participate in the program; and
22 7. Have at least two three active project areas in the program,
23 consisting either of one above the Canton Lake dam and one below,
